                <td bgcolor="#5A71AD" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2">spytfyre</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#5A71AD" valign="top"><font color="white" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/26/2003&nbsp;: 09:25:35 AM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> <br /><br />Bahh It’s been so long since I have played …… I logged in and checked.<br /><br />Alt +O Under the “Target” section of the “Keyboard Tab”..<br /><br /><b>Defaults key functions are:</b><br /><br /><b>TAB:</b> Toggles Target and YOU<br /><b>Un-mapped:</b> Toggles Last TWO Targets (This is the one they added, there is no 3 target one) Sorry for any confusion.<br /><br />I had/have them remapped to: <br /><br />TAB: Toggles Last TWO Targets<br />SHIFT TAB: Toggles Target and YOU<br /><br />To answer the original question:<br /><b>Mapping the overhead camera to a key and using your mouse to target is the way to go in a very tight spot with multiple mobs. Use keys to cast and hover mouse over next target while it’s casting.</b><br /><br /><br /><i>For the hell of it…..</i><br /><br />F1 - This targets you.<br />F2 - This targets the person in the first slot in the group window.<br />F3 - This targets the person in the second slot in the group window.<br />F4 - This targets the person in the third slot in the group window.<br />F5 - This targets the person in the fourth slot in the group window.<br />F6 - This targets the person in the fifth slot in the group window.<br />F7 - This targets the nearest PC within your field of vision. (Doesn’t always work)<br />F8 - This targets the nearest NPC within your field of vision. (Doesn’t always work)<br /><br />Hitting any of these function keys twice will target that character's pet, if there is one (including your own if you hit F1). You can remap all of the above and/or add alternate keys.<br /><br />Clicking the person’s health bar in the group window will target that person.<br /><br /><b>The NPC / PC that you have targeted is a different colour</b>. With 3 or 4 NPC’s with the same name it’s one way to tell your target. (You’d think this is obvious but it’s not to some)<br /><br />/assist (You’d think this is obvious too but so many people haven’t a clue or so it would seem)<br /><br />/assist playername 1  ex. Main Assist<br />/assist playername 2  ex. Second Assist<br />/assist playername 3  ex. Healer that may get pounded on during a bad pull etc etc..<br /><br /><b>H – quick and dirty line of sight test.</b> Hailing a target and having its name pop up means it can be cast on.<br /><br />Hope something helped</span></font></td>
              </tr>
